```

**Transaction Pattern:**
```java
// Initialize transaction
producer.initTransactions();

try {
    // Begin Kafka transaction
    producer.beginTransaction();

    // Process and send to Kafka
    ProducerRecord<String, String> record = new ProducerRecord<>(topic, key, value);
    producer.send(record);

    // Database operation with transaction ID
    String txId = UUID.randomUUID().toString();
    jdbcTemplate.update("INSERT INTO data_table VALUES (?, ?, ?)", 
        id, value, txId);

    // Commit offset only after DB success
    producer.sendOffsetsToTransaction(offsets, consumer);
    producer.commitTransaction();

} catch (Exception e) {
    producer.abortTransaction();
    // Retry logic with exponential backoff
}
```

## Failure Recovery Strategies

**Database Deduplication:**
- Unique constraint on transaction_id column
- INSERT IGNORE or ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING
- Periodic cleanup of processed transaction IDs

**Offset Management:**
- Manual offset commits after successful processing
- Store offsets in database for consistency
- Use consumer group coordination for failover

**Error Handling:**
- Circuit breaker pattern for database failures
- Dead-letter queue for unprocessable messages
- Monitoring and alerting for transaction failures

## Real-World Considerations

**Performance Trade-offs:**
- EOS=ALLS adds ~20% latency overhead
- Increased memory usage for transaction state
- Requires careful broker configuration (min.insync.replicas=2)

**Edge Cases:**
- Network partitions during commit phase
- Broker leadership changes mid-transaction
- Database connection pool exhaustion

**Monitoring:**
- Track transaction abort rates
- Monitor consumer lag during failures
- Alert on duplicate detection events
